04596nam a22005295i 9780774851404DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20072005xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748514047 a10.59962/97807748514042doi  a(DE-B1597)661466  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aE99.T6.C78 2005eb 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a979.81 aCruikshank, Julie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDo Glaciers Listen? :bLocal Knowledge, Colonial Encounters, and Social Imagination /cJulie Cruikshank. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2007] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (328 p.) :b23 b&w illustrations, 10 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBrenda and David McLean Canadian Studies00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tMatters of Locality -- tMemories of the Little Ice Age -- tConstructing Life Stories: Glaciers as Social Spaces -- tListening for Different Stories -- tPractices of Exploration -- tTwo Centuries of Stories from Lituya Bay: Nature, Culture, and La Pérouse -- tBringing Icy Regions Home: John Muir in Alaska -- tEdward James Glave, the Alsek, and the Congo -- tScientific Research in Sentient Places -- tMapping Boundaries: From Stories to Borders -- tMelting Glaciers and Emerging Histories -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDo Glaciers Listen? explores the conflicting depictions of glaciers to show how natural and cultural histories are objectively entangled in the Mount Saint Elias ranges. This rugged area, where Alaska, British Columbia, and the Yukon Territory now meet, underwent significant geophysical change in the late eighteenth and nineteenth centuries, which coincided with dramatic social upheaval resulting from European exploration and increased travel and trade among Aboriginal peoples. European visitors brought with them varying conceptions of nature as sublime, as spiritual, or as a resource for human progress. They saw glaciers as inanimate, subject to empirical investigation and measurement. Aboriginal oral histories, conversely, described glaciers as sentient, animate, and quick to respond to human behaviour. In each case, however, the experiences and ideas surrounding glaciers were incorporated into interpretations of social relations. Focusing on these contrasting views during the late stages of the Little Ice Age (1550-1900), Cruikshank demonstrates how local knowledge is produced, rather than discovered, through colonial encounters, and how it often conjoins social and biophysical processes. She then traces how the divergent views weave through contemporary debates about cultural meanings as well as current discussions about protected areas, parks, and the new World Heritage site. Readers interested in anthropology and Native and northern studies will find this a fascinating read and a rich addition to circumpolar literature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077485140440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774851404423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774851404/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  a978-3-11-141860-5  Univers